Download and look around in Visual Studio Express for Web. It's what we will be using at camp. http://www.visualstudio.com/en-us

Code Academy's Web Fundamentals will get you a head start on the basics of the web. http://www.codecademy.com/tracks/web

Code Academy's Web JavaScript gives a very basic overview of javascript, which is probably easiest to learn as a first language for first timers. http://www.codecademy.com/tracks/javascript

Another great JavaScript site is JavaScript Fundamentals: Development for Absolute Beginners. http://channel9.msdn.com/Series/HTML5-CSS3-Fundamentals-Development-for-Absolute-Beginners

If you have never written C#, but you understand the basics of programming, C# Fundamentals: Development for Absolute Beginners is a good place to start. http://channel9.msdn.com/Series/C-Sharp-Fundamentals-Development-for-Absolute-Beginners?page=2

For the more adventurous coders, the Microsoft ASP.NET MVC 5 site is a rather technical overview of the framework with a lot of videos. We will be using this in class as well, so the more familiar you are, the better. http://www.asp.net/mvc

The Plural Site Training is for MVC 5 and it is awesome. Free too. http://www.asp.net/mvc/pluralsight
